The '''Wiltshire cure''' is a traditional English technique for [[curing (food preservation)|curing]] [[bacon]] and [[ham]]. The technique originated in the 18th century in [[Calne]], [[Wiltshire]]; it was developed by the Harris family.<ref name=independent /> Originally it was a dry cure method that involved applying salt to the meat for 10–14 days.<ref name=Davidson /> Storing the meat in cold rooms meant that less salt was needed.<ref name=independent /> The Wiltshire cure has been a wet cure, soaking the meat in [[brine]] for 4–5 days, since the [[First World War]].<ref name=Davidson /><ref name=Piggott /> [[Smoking (cooking)|Smoking]] is not part of the process, although bacon is often smoked after being cured.<ref name=Davidson />
In 2010, several large British supermarket chains signed a voluntary code agreeing to use clearer labelling on [[pork]] products to avoid confusion over country of origin. For shops under this agreement, pork products sold in the UK that are labelled with "Wiltshire Cure" should only have been sourced from the UK.<ref name=guardian /> ==References== ;Footnotes {{Reflist|refs= <ref name=independent>{{Citation | title = The Cure for Bacon Lovers | work = [[The Independent]] | publisher = Independent Print Limited | date = 26 February 2000 | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/food-and-drink/features/the-cure-for-bacon-lovers-726169.html | accessdate =11 June 2011 }}</ref> <ref name=Davidson>[[#Davidson|Davidson & Jaine]], p. 50</ref> <ref name=Piggott>[[#Piggott|Piggott & Thirsk]], p. </ref> <ref name=guardian>{{Citation | last = Smillie | first = Susan | title = New Food Labelling Code Agreed for Pork | work = [[The Guardian]] | publisher = Guardian Media Group | date = 23 February 2010 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2010/feb/23/food-and-drink-farming | accessdate = 11 June 2011 }}</ref> }} ;Sources {{Refbegin}} *{{Citation | last = Davidson | first = Alan | last2 = Jaine | first2 = Tom | title = The Oxford Companion to Food | publisher = Oxford University Press | year = 2006 | isbn = 0-19-280681-5 | ref = Davidson}} *{{Citation | last = Piggott | first = Stuart | last2 = Thirsk | first2 = Joan | title = The Agrarian History of England and Wales: Volume 1, Prehistory to AD 1042 | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 2011 | isbn = 1-107-40114-3 | ref = Piggott}} {{Refend}}
